The most common sorting algorithms are bubble sort, insertion sort, selection sort, merge sort, quick sort, and heap sort. All these algorithms are used to order a list of elements in a sorted order. They work by repeatedly comparing adjacent elements and swapping them if they are in the wrong order. The time and space complexities of these algorithms vary, but they can be easily implemented in C++ using the following codes:

```c++
// implementation of bubble sort algorithm

void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
            if (arr[j] < arr[j + 1]) {
                // Swap arr[j] and arr[j + 1]
                int temp = arr[j];
                arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                arr[j + 1] = temp;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

